      • hasNext

        public Pullable.NextStatus hasNext()
        Description copied from interface: Pullable
        Determines if an event can be pulled from the output. Depending on what happens, the possible return values are:
        • If one of the inputs answers "no" when called for Pullable.hasNext(), returns "no"
        • If one of the inputs answers "maybe" when called for Pullable.hasNext(), returns "maybe"
        • If all inputs answer "yes" when called for Pullable.hasNext(), but no event is produced with the given inputs, returns "maybe"
        • Otherwise, returns "yes"
        Therefore, the method is lazy in that it asks events from its input only once, and attempts to produce an output event only once.
        Specified by:
        hasNext in interface Pullable
        Returns:
        Whether a next event exists

      • hasNextHard

        public Pullable.NextStatus hasNextHard()
        Description copied from interface: Pullable
        Determines if an event can be pulled from the output, by trying "harder" than Pullable.hasNext(). Depending on what happens, the possible return values are:
        • If one of the inputs answers "no" when called for Pullable.hasNext(), returns "no"
        • If all inputs answer "yes" when called for Pullable.hasNext(), and an event is produced with the given inputs, returns "yes"
        • Otherwise, the method will keep calling Pullable.hasNextHard() on the inputs as long as they don't answer "no", and will try to produce an output event until one is produced.
        • To avoid infinite looping, the method eventually gives up (and answers "no") after some maximum number of repetitions is reached. This is configured by the static field Pullable.s_maxRetries.
        Specified by:
        hasNextHard in interface Pullable
        Returns:
        Whether a next event exists
